Dear Governor Perdue,

     I'm writing in my capacity as President of Alamance Community College to request that you consider exempting community colleges from the 5% reversion being implemented by Executive Order 21.  With community colleges initially taking a greater percentage cut (6.8%)  from last year's budget than public schools (5%) or the university system (5.8%), we started out in a worse position then either of the other two educational systems.

     Alamance Community College has experienced an 18% increase in headcount and a 22% increase in FTEs this fall over last fall.  Our county unemployment rate is currently  12.6% - higher than the State average.  We have worked diligently to insure we are providing classes for those who most need our services.  With such hefty enrollment increases, plus the 20% increase in tuition, the State has a very significant increase in tuition revenues going to the General Fund.  Where the universities are keeping their tuition revenue increase thus making their plight less urgent, we are not permitted to do so.

     If the 5% reversion is implemented, this will mean Alamance Community College will be required to return an additional $890K, on top of the management flexibility sum of $524K - all of this occurring at a time when we are trying to do our best to retrain those unemployed workers who are enrolling in unprecedented numbers.  We have made the commitment to absorb these additional students without increasing our class sizes, because many of these individuals are in need of developmental classes which necessitate a greater commitment of time from the instructors.  We have taken the drastic steps of adding 7 a.m. classes, because we are at room capacity during our normal operating times.  While we have increased online and hybrid courses, it still isn't enough to meet all the needs.  

     Any consideration you can give to exempting us from the 5% reversion would put us more in line with the university system's
 bottom line.  Our systemwide enrollment increases and tuition increase of 20% should come close to offsetting the 5% reversion amount.

     I thank you for your time reviewing this request.

